(111, 1, '2023-10-30 05:07:11', '2023-10-30 05:07:11', '<div></div>\n<div>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Introduction:</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the middle of the 19th century, realism painting became prominent and began to subvert the romanticism and idealism that were then popular. Realist art sought to capture the world unaltered by embellishment or idealized distortions, stemming from the conviction that art ought to represent the truth of ordinary life. This essay examines the salient features, significant practitioners, and long-lasting effects of Realism painting.</span>\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-112 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost/trasua/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Screenshot-2023-10-30-at-12.04.08.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1196\" height=\"544\" />\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong>Definition and Key Characteristics:</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Realism art is characterized by its objective depiction of the world, emphasizing precise representation and attention to detail. It seeks to faithfully capture the physical appearance of subjects, whether they are people, landscapes, or objects. Realist artists strive for accuracy, often employing techniques such as careful observation, meticulous brushwork, and a naturalistic color palette. By focusing on ordinary subjects and the mundane aspects of life, Realism challenges the hierarchy of traditional art and redefines what can be considered artistically significant.</span>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n 	<li><strong> Influential Artists:</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Gustave Courbet: Regarded as the progenitor of Realism, Courbet tackled contemporary social and political themes in his artwork. His painting \"The Stone Breakers\" is a potent illustration of the movement, showing workers in an unvarnished and raw way and bringing attention to the struggles the working class faces.</span>\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-113 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost/trasua/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Screenshot-2023-10-30-at-12.05.29.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1194\" height=\"612\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jean-François Millet: The realities of the agrarian society were made more visible by Millet\'s depictions of rural life and peasant work. Inspiring empathy and social consciousness, his famous painting \"The Gleaners\" depicts the dignity and hardship of rural laborers.</span>\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-117 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost/trasua/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Screenshot-2023-10-30-at-12.07.10-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1194\" height=\"878\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Winslow Homer: Homer was an American Realist painter who specialized in depicting scenes from everyday life, especially those of rural communities and fishermen. His paintings, like \"The Gulf Stream\" and \"Snap the Whip,\" capture the wonders and struggles of rural America and life at sea.</span>\n\n</div>', 'Realism Art: Capturing Life\'s Essence', 'A generous donation by artist Lorraine Jenyns and her family of 25 prints, drawings and sculptures by her late husband, the artist Bob Jenyns, adds significantly to an existing collection of his works acquired by the Gallery in the 1980s. Former Gallery Director Margaret Rich recalls her friendship with Bob Jenyns.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '62-autosave-v1', '', '', '2023-10-30 05:07:11', '2023-10-30 05:07:11', '', 62, 'http://localhost/trasua/?p=111', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
